Backdoor Attack Detection and Defense System

This project provides a complete backdoor attack detection and defense pipeline, consisting of three stages: poisoned sample detection, clean sample identification, and trigger verification with model retraining.
System Requirements
•	Python 3.7+
•	PyTorch 1.8+
•	Transformers 4.0+
•	scikit-learn
•	scipy
•	matplotlib
•	pandas
•	nltk
Installation
bash
pip install torch transformers scikit-learn scipy matplotlib pandas nltk


Data Preparation
1.	Download the dataset (e.g., SST-2 ) and place it in the following directory structure:
data/
└── sentiment_data/
    └── SST-2/
        ├── train.tsv
        └── dev.tsv
2.	Download the victim model (e.g.., bert-base-uncased) to a local directory:
bash
# Using the transformers library
from transformers import BertModel
model = BertModel.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased')
model.save_pretrained('./bert-base-uncased')

Running the Pipeline
Stage 1: Poisoned Sample Detection (detect_poison.py)
This stage aims to detect samples that have been poisoned by backdoor attacks.
Run command:
bash
python detect_poison.py
Generate output files:
o	clean_feature.txt - clean sample features
o	clean_sentence.txt - clean sample sentences
o	poison_feature.txt - poisoned sample features
o	poison_sentence.txt - poisoned sample sentences
o	detected_poison_sentence.txt - detected poisoned sentences
o	detected_poison_feature.txt - detected poisoned features
o	adaptive_detection_analysis.png - visualization of detection results
Stage 2: Clean Sample Identification (detect_clean.py)
This stage aims to identify high-precision clean samples from all samples.
Run command:
python detect_clean.py
Main functions:
Generate output files:
o	detected_clean_sentence.txt - detected clean sentences
o	clean_detection_results.txt - detailed detection results
o	Visualization charts showing KL1-KL2 distribution and detection results
Stage 3: Trigger Verification and Model Retraining (filter_train.py)
This stage aims to verify the trigger and retrain a clean model after removing poisoned samples.
Run command:
bash
python filter_train.py

Save defended model to ./trained_models/defended/pytorch_model.bin
Output Files Description
Stage 1 Outputs:
•	clean_feature.txt / poison_feature.txt - feature vectors (KL1, KL2, ProbDiff)
•	clean_sentence.txt / poison_sentence.txt - corresponding text sentences
•	detected_poison_sentence.txt - detected poisoned samples
•	adaptive_detection_analysis.png - visualization of detection results
Stage 2 Outputs:
•	detected_clean_sentence.txt - detected clean samples
•	clean_detection_results.txt - detailed detection results and statistics
Stage 3 Outputs:
•	Defended model saved at ./trained_models/defended/pytorch_model.bin
•	Performance comparison results printed to console
Important Notes
1.	Execution Order: Must execute in Stage 1 → Stage 2 → Stage 3 order
2.	Data Dependencies: Each stage depends on output files from previous stages
3.	Computational Resources: BERT model training requires GPU support for reasonable speed
4.	Memory Requirements: Sufficient memory is needed for large datasets (recommended 16GB+)



plot-3d.py 
This is a 3D visualization program for generating distribution comparison plots of clean and poisoned samples in a three-dimensional feature space. The program reads the feature files `clean_feature.txt` and `poison_feature.txt` generated by `detect_poison.py` (containing three feature values: KL1, KL2, and ProbDiff) and creates four different types of 3D scatter plots from multiple viewing angles (30° elevation with four azimuth angles: 45°, 225°, 315°, and 135°). These visualizations clearly show the distribution patterns, overlapping regions, and separability of the two types of samples in 3D space, helping to intuitively understand the characteristics of the feature space in backdoor attack detection.
